Question 1

A student was asked to complete an assignment where they collected a sample of data on a single variable and tested a reasonable hypothesis about that variable.

They chose to measure the number of text messages they sent each day over a two-week period. From this sample, they calculated a sample mean of \(\bar{x} = 81.2\) messages per day and a sample standard deviation of \(s = 12.45\).

They chose to test the following:

\(H_0: \mu = 81.2\)

\(H_1: \mu \neq 81.2\)

After confirming that the data were approximately normally distributed, they conducted a one-sample t-test and obtained a non-significant p-value at the \(\alpha = 0.05\) level.

What are your thoughts about their approach? Identify and explain at least two important issues with their reasoning or methodology.


Question 2

To reduce cheating in a crowded lecture hall, an instructor prepared two versions of a midterm exam. Each version consisted of 35 questions randomly drawn from a larger pool of questions, so that each student received a different exam from the person sitting next to them.

The exam results for the two versions are provided in classroom.csv, which includes a variable indicating which version each student received along with their percentage score.

Use appropriate statistical reasoning to evaluate whether some students were unfairly disavantaged by this approach. You must form a clear decision (no fence sitting).


Question 3

Assume the exams described in the previous question are unfair. What is one basic statistical approach that could be used to remedy this state of affairs? (No calculations are required for your answer. Describe the approach conceptually.)


Question 4

Garfield is a fictional orange cat, known for his hatred of Mondays, love of food, and his tendency to overeat (especially lasagna). A veterinarian claims that a typical indoor cat should consume no more than 250 calories per day to maintain a healthy weight.

A researcher collects a random sample of cats similar to Garfield (e.g., orange, indoor, adult, hates Mondays, similar size, and lifestyle) from different households. Each cats daily calorie intake is measured for a single day. The data (in calories) are provided in garfield.csv.

Using this sample, evaluate whether we can accept the claim that cats like Garfield tend to consume more than the veterinarians recommended daily amount.

Report the following:

  • \(H_0\) and \(H_1\)
  • test statistic
  • p-value
  • confidence interval
  • conclusion

Question 5

Use a robust method of outlier detection to determine if there are any outliers in the garfield.csv data. If outliers are present, report just the names of the cats considered outliers in alphabetical order.


Question 6

The dataset book_banning.csv lists books that have been (and attempted to be) banned across the United States. The documentation for the dataset can be read here: https://vincentarelbundock.github.io/Rdatasets/doc/bayesrules/book_banning.html

Create a bar plot comparing the proportion of successfull attempts to ban books on the basis of LGBTQ material in republican and democrat leaning states (i.e., there should be two bars displayed, one for democrats and one for republicans). Display a dataframe that lists the proportions you used in the plot.


Question 7

Two psychology students, Kalyn and Rachael, participated in different experiments that measured reaction time in a behavioural task. Kalyns reaction time was 979 milliseconds in an experiment where the mean reaction time was 1052 milliseconds with a standard deviation of 50 milliseconds. Rachaels reaction time was 902 milliseconds in a different experiment where the mean reaction time was 1082 milliseconds with a standard deviation of 56 milliseconds. Who performed faster relative to the other participants in their respective experiment?


Question 8

A neuroscientist is studying how consistently neurons respond to repeated visual stimuli. In an experiment, a neuron in the primary visual cortex (V1) is repeatedly shown the same image, and its firing rate (in spikes per second, Hz) is recorded during a fixed stimulus window.

Previous research suggests that this neurons firing rate under these conditions follows an approximately normal distribution with a mean of 18.2 Hz and a standard deviation of 4.7 Hz.

Using this model, what is the probability that the neurons firing rate exceeds 15 Hz on a randomly selected trial?


Question 9

In a normal distribution, small, medium, and large effect sizes are conventionally defined as Cohens d values of 0.2, 0.5, and 0.8, respectively.

Assuming the data are normally distributed, what percentage of the total area under the curve lies between the mean and each of these effect size values?


Question 10

A comparative psychologist is investigating stress responses in captive animals. It is hypothesized that animals housed in high-density enclosures (i.e., enclosures with lots of conspecifics) exhibit higher levels of physiological stress than those housed in enriched, low-density environments (i.e., enclosures with few conspecifics and additional toys and environmental features).

Stress was operationally defined in terms of cortisol concentration (g/dL) from saliva samples, with higher concentrations being indicative of greater stress. Independent random samples were collected from two groups of animals at zoos across the country:

  • High density enclosures
  • Enriched, low density enclosures

The data can be found in animal_enclosure.csv. Each observation repsents one animals measured cortisol concentration.

Conduct a test to evaluate whether we can accept the psychologists hypothesis. Ensure the test is designed so that the probability of incorrectly rejecting the null is only 1 in 100.

Report the following:

  • \(H_0\) and \(H_1\)
  • test statistic
  • p-value
  • confidence interval
  • conclusion

Question 11

Irrespective of your result in the previous question, suppose the test found a statistically significant difference between the two groups. Are we entitled to conclude that high-density enclosures caused greater stress than low-density enclosures? Explain your reasoning.


Question 12

Suppose the sample size for each group in the animal_enclosure.csv data was increased to 100 animals, while the sample means and standard deviations remained the same. Without recomputing the test, would the p-value increase, decrease, or stay the same? Explain your reasoning.
